"""
MKT Context Commentary — Romans chapters 8–10
Historical, cultural, and background commentary for each verse.
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-romans-8-10.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ROMANS = {
  "8": {
    "1": '<p>The Roman legal term <em>condemnatio</em> (condemnation) referred to the formal guilty verdict pronounced by the magistrate after trial; the condemned person was subject to the full penalty of the law — fine, exile, or death. Paul\'s declaration that there is "no condemnation" for those in Christ borrows this courtroom vocabulary to announce that the divine tribunal has pronounced final acquittal. Roman Christians in a city where legal proceedings and public penalties were visible daily would have grasped the forensic weight of this language immediately.</p>',
    "2": '<p>In Second Temple Judaism the Torah was frequently called the "law of life" — Sirach 17:11 states that God gave Israel "the law of life as his own possession." The Qumran community (Dead Sea Scrolls) spoke of the "laws of truth" that the Spirit of truth leads the faithful into (1QS 3:7-9). Paul\'s phrase "law of the Spirit of life" stands in this tradition while redefining what "law of life" means: not Torah-observance but the Spirit\'s operative power in the new covenant (Ezek 36:26-27).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Levitical sin-offering system (Lev 4-5) required specific animals for specific categories of sin, with the priest offering blood on behalf of the guilty party to make atonement. The LXX phrase <em>peri hamartias</em> (for sin / as a sin offering) appears over 50 times in Leviticus alone as the technical term for the hattat offering. Paul\'s use of the same phrase for Christ\'s mission connects his death directly to the Levitical sacrificial system while indicating that the system has been brought to its intended fulfillment. The temple sacrificial system was still operational when Romans was written (c. 57 CE); Paul\'s readers would have known the Levitical background.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The idea that the law\'s requirements might be fulfilled "in us" rather than "by us" reflects the new-covenant promise of Jeremiah 31:33 — God would write the law on the heart rather than on stone tablets. Ezekiel\'s parallel promise (Ezek 36:27) is even more specific: "I will put my Spirit within you and cause you to walk in my statutes." Both prophets envisioned a future in which the divine Spirit would accomplish internally what external law-keeping could not. Paul reads this promise as the present reality of the new-covenant community.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The Stoic philosophers used the concept of "following nature" (<em>kata physin zēn</em>) to describe the life of wisdom: the wise person orders their inner life according to logos (reason/nature). Jewish writers like Philo adapted this framework, describing the person who lives according to the Torah as the one who "follows nature." Paul\'s <em>kata sarka / kata pneuma</em> (according to flesh / according to Spirit) antithesis engages the same philosophical question about the fundamental orientation of human existence but relocates the governing principle from reason/nature to the divine Spirit.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Jewish two-inclination (yetzer) doctrine, developed in rabbinic literature but with roots in Second Temple Judaism, held that each person has both a good inclination (yetzer hatov) and an evil inclination (yetzer hara). The evil inclination was associated with the bodily appetites and with the impulse toward rebellion against God. Paul\'s "mindset of the flesh = death" is conceptually related but more radical: the flesh-orientation is not merely a competing impulse but the fundamental condition of unregenerate humanity, which only the Spirit can reverse — not moral discipline alone.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Greco-Roman philosophical traditions debated whether passion or reason should govern human life. The Stoics argued that the passions (<em>pathē</em>) must be subordinated to reason; uncontrolled passion was seen as the root of moral failure. Paul\'s diagnosis is more fundamental: the problem is not passions vs. reason but the entire "flesh" orientation vs. the Spirit. The flesh does not merely resist the law emotionally; it is incapable of submission (<em>ou dunaton</em>) — a category impossibility, not merely a practical difficulty.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The phrase "in the flesh" (<em>en sarki</em>) functions in Paul as a spatial-sphere descriptor rather than purely a moral category. First-century readers familiar with Jewish apocalyptic would have understood the "flesh" as describing the present evil age, the sphere of Adam\'s sin and mortality. Paul contrasts this with "in the Spirit" as the sphere of the new age, inaugurated by the resurrection. The two spheres overlap in the present: believers live in the overlap, embodied in the old creation while belonging to the new.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The Spirit of God dwelling within (<em>oikeō en hymin</em>) is the fulfillment of the new-covenant promises in Ezekiel 36 and 37 (the valley of dry bones given the breath/spirit of God). In Second Temple Judaism, the Spirit was associated with the age to come; the Qumran community saw themselves as already receiving the Spirit in an anticipatory way. For Paul, the Spirit\'s indwelling is the decisive mark of belonging to the new creation rather than the old, and thus of being in the Messiah rather than in Adam.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The tension between the body being "dead because of sin" and the spirit being "alive because of righteousness" reflects the eschatological overlap of the ages. Believers already participate in the new-creation life (the spirit alive), while still inhabiting mortal bodies subject to Adam\'s death sentence (the body dead). This is the already/not-yet structure of Paul\'s eschatology: the resurrection age has begun (first in Christ, then in the Spirit\'s firstfruits), but the full transformation of the body awaits the parousia.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The resurrection of Jesus was the central historical claim of early Christianity and the lens through which Paul reads all else. In Jewish apocalyptic thought, the resurrection of the dead was associated with the final judgment at the end of the age (Dan 12:2; 2 Macc 7:14; 1 Enoch 51). Paul\'s argument is that God\'s raising of Jesus was the beginning of this end-of-age resurrection — the "firstfruits" (1 Cor 15:20-23). The Spirit who raised Jesus now dwells in believers as the guarantee that their bodies will also be raised.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Roman society was structured around the concept of debt-obligation (<em>debitum</em>). Clients owed patrons; freed slaves owed their former masters certain continuing obligations (<em>obsequium</em>). Paul\'s use of "debtors" (<em>opheiletai</em>) invokes this social framework to clarify what the gospel has ended: the old obligation to the flesh-power that once governed life. The debt has been cancelled by the death-with-Christ transaction described in ch6; no further payment is owed to the old master.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The language of "mortification of the deeds of the body" became formative for Christian ascetic practice in subsequent centuries. However, Paul\'s emphasis here is not on physical asceticism (bodily fasting, denial) but on Spirit-empowered renunciation of the flesh\'s deeds — the actions that express the old-Adam orientation. The instrument is the Holy Spirit, not willpower, differentiating Paul\'s ethic from Stoic self-mastery or Jewish law-observance as the path to moral life.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The concept of being "led" by the Spirit evokes both the OT imagery of divine guidance (the pillar of cloud/fire in the wilderness; the Spirit leading Ezekiel, Isa 63:14) and the Hellenistic philosophical idea of following the divine logos. For Paul, the Spirit\'s guidance is the mark of sonship in a way that Torah-observance alone was not: the children of God are those who respond to the Spirit\'s leading, a community defined by spiritual relationship rather than ethnic-covenantal identity.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Roman adoption law (<em>adoptio</em>) was a complex legal procedure by which a person became fully a member of a new family, with all rights of natural children including inheritance. The adoptee was legally free of all obligations to the former family and took on the full status of the new family. Paul\'s <em>huiothesia</em> (adoption) draws on this Roman institution to describe the believer\'s full family membership in God\'s household. The Aramaic <em>Abba</em> preserved in Greek-speaking churches signals that this cry originated in the earliest Aramaic-speaking Palestinian communities and was taken over by Gentile believers as a mark of authentic prayer.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Jewish legal tradition (following Deut 19:15) required two witnesses for a matter to be established. Paul\'s mention of the Spirit witnessing together with our spirit may invoke this double-witness principle: our inner conviction alone is not sufficient, but the Spirit\'s co-testimony with our spirit constitutes the two witnesses required for certainty of sonship. The Spirit as a witness appears in the Johannine tradition as well (1 John 5:6-8; John 15:26-27), suggesting an early Christian pneumatology of the Spirit as the definitive divine witness.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Roman inheritance law (<em>hereditas</em>) gave legitimate heirs the right to the full estate of the paterfamilias. Co-heirs (<em>coheredes</em>) shared the inheritance equally, regardless of individual contribution to the estate\'s creation. Paul\'s <em>sygklēronomoi Christou</em> (co-heirs with Christ) makes the eschatological inheritance available to all in Christ, not by their own merit but by the shared status of sonship. The co-suffering condition reflects the early Christian experience of persecution as participation in Christ\'s own sufferings (see Phil 1:29; Col 1:24; 1 Pet 4:13).</p>',
    "18": '<p>Paul wrote Romans from Corinth approximately 57-58 CE, during a period when Roman provincial governance frequently involved confiscation of property, social discrimination, and physical danger for those who belonged to emerging religious movements outside established Roman religion. The "sufferings of the present time" were not abstract for Paul, who himself had been flogged, imprisoned, stoned, and shipwrecked (2 Cor 11:23-27). The comparative weight between present suffering and coming glory uses the OT concept of eschatological reversal: the suffering righteous are vindicated (Isa 40:10; 61:7).</p>',
    "19": '<p>The Jewish apocalyptic tradition expected a cosmic renewal at the end of the age. 4 Ezra (c. 90 CE) speaks of creation "moaning" and "groaning" under the burden of the present evil age. 2 Baruch similarly envisions creation\'s transformation at the eschaton. Paul draws on this tradition to ground the cosmic hope of vv19-22. The personification of creation as an eager watcher may also echo Isa 55:12-13 (the trees clapping their hands) and Rom 8:26 (the groaning Spirit) — a trio of intercessions: creation groans, believers groan, the Spirit groans.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The Genesis narrative of the fall (Gen 3:17-19) describes the ground being cursed "because of you" (Adam\'s sin): futility and thorns are the consequence of human rebellion on the non-human creation. Jewish apocalyptic literature consistently understood the present disorder of creation as flowing from Adam\'s sin (2 Bar 56:5-7; 4 Ezra 7:11-14). The eschatological expectation is that the restoration of humanity will bring the restoration of creation. Paul stands in this tradition: the liberation of creation from futility is tied to the liberation of God\'s children.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The "liberty of the glory of the children of God" connects two OT streams: the Exodus liberation (<em>eleutherōthēsetai</em> echoing the Exodus redemption language) and the Isaianic new-creation promise (Isa 65:17-25; 66:22: "a new heavens and a new earth"). Paul\'s vision of cosmic redemption was unusual even within Jewish apocalyptic, which more commonly expected the destruction of the old creation rather than its renewal. The continuity Paul affirms — this creation liberated, not replaced — grounds his creation theology.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Birth-pang imagery (<em>ōdinō</em>) for the sufferings that precede the messianic age is pervasive in Jewish apocalyptic: the "woes of the Messiah" (<em>chevlei hamashiach</em>) in rabbinic literature, and "the birth pangs of the new age" in 1 Enoch, 2 Bar, and the Synoptic apocalypses (Mark 13:8 uses the same Greek word <em>ōdinōn</em> for "birth pangs"). Paul applies this imagery to the entire creation\'s experience: the present cosmic suffering is not random but purposive — the labor of the old creation giving birth to the new.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The agricultural term <em>aparchē</em> (firstfruits) was central to the Jewish festival calendar: the first sheaf of the harvest was offered to God as a pledge and as a guarantee of the full harvest to come (Lev 23:10-11; Deut 26:1-11). Paul uses this liturgical-agricultural image for the Spirit: the Spirit is the first installment (cf. 2 Cor 1:22: <em>arrabōn</em> = down payment) of the full eschatological life that believers will receive at the resurrection. The "redemption of the body" picks up the exodus-redemption language: the full <em>apolytrōsis</em> will be the bodily resurrection.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Jewish and Greek traditions both discussed the nature of hope. The Platonic tradition distinguished between the empirical knowledge of present things and hope/belief about the future (Philebus 39-40). Paul\'s point is phenomenological: hope by definition is directed toward what is not yet seen; to see the object is to move from hope to possession. The already-received salvation (aorist passive <em>esōthēmen</em>) exists in the mode of hope — completed in its foundational act, still awaiting its final disclosure.</p>',
    "25": '<p><em>Hypomonē</em> (patient endurance) was a prized virtue in both Jewish and Greco-Roman ethics, but with different grounds. The Stoic <em>hypomonē</em> was the wise person\'s rational acceptance of whatever fortune brings; it was based on philosophical detachment. Jewish <em>hypomonē</em> (especially in apocalyptic contexts: Dan 12:12; Rev 13:10; Jas 1:3-4) was patient endurance rooted in confidence in God\'s vindication of the faithful. Paul\'s use combines both: endurance grounded in the certainty of the eschatological hope rather than in philosophical detachment or grim perseverance.</p>',
    "26": '<p>In Jewish liturgical tradition, the synagogue prayer called the <em>Amidah</em> (the standing prayer, recited three times daily) included the acknowledgment that prayer itself requires divine aid. The <em>Aleinu</em> and other prayers express the community\'s dependence on God to accept imperfect worship. Paul\'s point that "we do not know what we ought to pray for" connects with this tradition of human inadequacy before God, but extends it: the Spirit\'s intercession is not a supplement to otherwise-adequate prayer but supplies what human prayer is structurally incapable of providing.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The divine attribute of "searching hearts" (<em>kardiognōstēs</em> — heart-knower, used of God in Acts 1:24 and 15:8, and implied in Ps 139, Jer 17:10, and many OT texts) was a standard element of Jewish prayer and theology. God is the one before whom all hearts are open. Paul uses this attribute specifically in relation to the Spirit\'s intercession: the God who searches all hearts recognizes the Spirit\'s groaning prayers as perfectly aligned with his own will. The divine self-communication (Spirit interceding to God) is a form of divine self-prayer within the Godhead.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Belief in divine <em>providentia</em> (providence) was shared by Stoics, Jewish thinkers like Josephus and Philo, and mainstream Greco-Roman religion. The Stoic version held that the <em>logos</em> orders all things toward rational ends; Josephus (Ant. 10.280) attributes to Daniel the view that providence governs all events. Paul\'s "all things work together for good" is not a generic optimism but a covenantal claim grounded in God\'s election-purpose (<em>prothesis</em>) and specific to "those who love God" — a divine-sovereignty claim, not Stoic fatalism.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The term <em>proginōskō</em> (foreknow) appears in Jewish election theology in ways that suggest more than mere temporal prescience. The divine "knowing" of Israel in the OT often carries the sense of covenantal election (Amos 3:2: "You only have I known of all the families of the earth"; Gen 18:19 in Hebrew uses "yada" for God\'s knowing of Abraham). The Greek translation of these texts and Qumran documents on the divine foreknowledge of the elect (1QS 3-4, 1QH) provide the background for Paul\'s usage: "foreknow" = "choose in advance in covenantal love."</p>',
    "30": '<p>The "golden chain" of vv29-30 — foreknow, predestine, call, justify, glorify — became foundational for Reformed soteriology (the <em>ordo salutis</em> debate). But Paul\'s chain is not a temporal sequence of individual experiences; it is a theological summary of God\'s sovereign action from eternity to eternity. The past tense of "glorified" (<em>edoxasen</em>) is the most striking feature: from God\'s perspective, the glorification of the elect is already accomplished, so certain is the divine purpose. This prophetic-perfect usage appears in OT prophets (Isa 53: "he was wounded" as past).</p>',
    "31": '<p>The rhetorical questions of vv31-35 follow the pattern of the Jewish liturgical form known as the <em>diatribe</em> (imaginary dialogue with an objector), which Paul uses throughout Romans. But the content of vv31-39 is also close to the Psalmic lament-and-confidence pattern: Psalm 118, 44, 22, and 89 all follow the structure of naming the threat and then asserting divine faithfulness. Paul\'s doxology is a transposed Psalm of confidence, grounded not in past acts of deliverance but in the cross and resurrection as the definitive divine act.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The Aqedah (the binding of Isaac, Gen 22) was one of the most theologically developed narratives in Second Temple Judaism. Jewish texts celebrate Abraham\'s willingness to sacrifice Isaac as the supreme test of faith (Jubilees 17-18; Ps-Philo, L.A.B. 32; 4Q225). The Aqedah was associated with atonement theology: Isaac\'s near-sacrifice on Moriah was interpreted as atoning merit for future generations. Paul echoes the Genesis language (Gen 22:16 LXX: <em>ouk epheisō</em>) but applies it to the Father not sparing his own Son — the divine Aqedah that the human Aqedah foreshadowed.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The term "elect" (<em>eklektoi</em>) was used by the Qumran community for themselves as the chosen ones of God, the true Israel within Israel. In Deutero-Isaiah, the Servant of the Lord is called God\'s elect (Isa 42:1), and the people are God\'s elect (Isa 45:4; 65:9). Paul applies the term to the entire community of those in Christ — Jew and Gentile alike — who constitute the eschatological people of God. The question "who will bring a charge against God\'s elect?" echoes the Servant vindication passage of Isa 50:8-9, where the Servant asks the same question and answers that it is the Lord who vindicates him.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The session of Christ at God\'s right hand (Ps 110:1) was among the earliest christological proof-texts in the NT church (Mark 12:36; Acts 2:34-35; Heb 1:3; 8:1). The heavenly intercession of the exalted Christ was developed most fully in Hebrews (7:25), but Paul assumes it here: the risen, ascended, enthroned Christ intercedes for his people. This heavenly priesthood is the NT equivalent of the Levitical Day of Atonement, when the High Priest entered the Most Holy Place to intercede for Israel — now actualized permanently in Christ\'s session.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The list of hardships in v35 (tribulation, distress, persecution, famine, nakedness, danger, sword) reflects the actual experience of early Christian communities in the Roman empire. Nero\'s persecution (64 CE) was still in the future when Romans was written, but social ostracism, property confiscation, and periodic violence were already realities for communities that refused participation in civic religion and the emperor cult. The Roman Christians would have read this list as describing their current situation rather than as hypothetical dangers.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Psalm 44 is a community lament in which Israel cries out over military defeat despite covenant faithfulness: "for your sake we face death all day long; we are considered as sheep to be slaughtered" (Ps 44:22). The Psalm was interpreted in rabbinic tradition as relevant to martyrdom situations (cf. b. Gittin 57b on Ps 44:22). Paul cites it to interpret the community\'s present suffering not as divine abandonment (the Psalmist\'s fear) but as participation in the Messiah\'s death — a transformed hermeneutic of suffering.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The word Paul apparently coined — <em>hypernikaō</em> (to super-conquer) — would have resonated in a world saturated with the imagery of Roman military triumph (<em>triumphus</em>). The Roman triumph was the highest honor: the victorious general paraded through Rome with his captives and spoils. Paul\'s irony is that the apparent defeat (persecution, suffering) is in fact a super-victory over the powers that inflict it, because those powers cannot separate the believer from Christ\'s love. The victory is won in the suffering, not after it.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"Angels," "rulers," and "powers" in first-century Jewish and early Christian cosmology referred to angelic/supernatural beings who governed nations and cosmic spheres (Dan 10:13-21; 1 Enoch 6-11; Col 1:16; 2:15; Eph 6:12). The question of whether such beings might separate believers from Christ was not abstract: mystery religions and Jewish apocalyptic both wrestled with the power of intermediate beings. Paul\'s list catalogs every possible category of such powers and declares none of them adequate to break the love-bond established by the cross.</p>',
    "39": '<p>The final phrase "the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord" locates the entire doxology of ch8 in its proper center. The love of God is not an abstract divine attribute but a specific historical act (the cross) and a continuing relationship (union with the risen Christ). The movement of the chapter — from "no condemnation" (v1) to "no separation" (v39) — mirrors the movement of the gospel itself: from forensic acquittal to relational security. Both are grounded in the same event: the death and resurrection of Jesus Christ.</p>'
  },
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>Paul\'s triple attestation — "I speak truth in Christ, I am not lying, my conscience confirms through the Holy Spirit" — is unusual even for Paul, who typically is more direct in asserting his authority. The three levels of attestation (Christ, personal oath, Spirit-enlightened conscience) may reflect the Jewish legal requirement of multiple witnesses (Deut 19:15) applied to a particularly difficult claim — that Paul (the apostle to the Gentiles) genuinely grieves over Israel. Roman and Jewish readers might have suspected that a Gentile-mission apostle had abandoned concern for his own people.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Paul\'s emotional vocabulary here — <em>lypē megalē</em> (great grief) and <em>adialeipton odynē</em> (unceasing anguish) — draws on the tradition of the lamenting prophet. Jeremiah grieved over Jerusalem\'s destruction (Jer 4:19: "My anguish, my anguish! I writhe in pain!"). Moses wished to be blotted out of the book for Israel\'s sake (Exod 32:32). The intensity of Paul\'s grief signals that chs9-11 are not a merely academic excursion into theodicy but pastoral anguish over the people who are "his own" (<em>hoi syngeneis mou kata sarka</em> — my kin according to the flesh).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The concept of <em>anathema</em> (the Greek translation of Hebrew <em>cherem</em> — devoted-to-destruction, irrevocably cut off from the community of God) was the most extreme form of religious exclusion. The Qumran community used <em>cherem</em>-language for expulsion from the community. Paul\'s wish to be <em>anathema from Christ</em> for Israel\'s sake deliberately echoes Moses\'s prayer in Exod 32:32 ("blot me out of your book") and demonstrates the logic of substitutionary intercession: the greatest good (union with Christ) wished away for the sake of others\' salvation.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The six covenantal privileges Paul lists were standard elements of Jewish self-understanding in the Second Temple period. The <em>doxa</em> (glory) refers to the Shekinah — the divine presence that dwelled in the tabernacle and temple (Exod 40:34-35; 1 Kgs 8:10-11). The <em>diathēkai</em> (covenants, plural) encompasses the Abrahamic (Gen 15, 17), Mosaic (Exod 19-24), Davidic (2 Sam 7), and new covenant (Jer 31:31-34) promises. The <em>nomothesia</em> (giving of the law) at Sinai was celebrated in Jewish tradition as the greatest divine gift to Israel. Paul is not minimizing these privileges but insisting on their genuine reality before addressing why Israel\'s unbelief has not nullified God\'s word.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The question of whether Paul is ascribing divinity to Christ in v5b has been debated since the early church. The syntax most naturally supports a Christological doxology: "from them is the Christ according to the flesh, the one who is over all, God blessed forever." If Paul is ascribing divinity to Christ here, it is one of the clearest such statements in his letters, paralleling his other high-Christological passages (Phil 2:6; Col 1:15-20; 2 Cor 4:4). The divine name in Jewish doxologies was always YHWH; applying such a doxology to Christ is a bold theological claim.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The phrase "the word of God has not failed" (<em>ou... ekpeptōken ho logos tou theou</em>) addresses the central theodicy question of chs9-11: if Israel is God\'s covenant people, why has so much of Israel rejected the Messiah? The answer is that "Israel" was always a category defined by divine election rather than biological descent — a distinction already present in the OT (Isa 10:22-23 on the remnant; Mal 1:2-3 on Jacob and Esau). Paul is not inventing a new theological move but drawing out implications already embedded in the prophetic witness.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Genesis narrative of Isaac and Ishmael (Gen 16, 17, 21) established early in Israel\'s story that biological descent from Abraham did not automatically constitute membership in the promise-line. Ishmael was Abraham\'s physical son but was not the child of the promise; the promise-line ran through Isaac alone. Philo of Alexandria also used the Isaac/Ishmael contrast to describe the difference between earthly and spiritual offspring (Allegorical Interpretation 3.87-88; On Sobriety 7-9). Paul stands in a tradition of allegorical/typological reading of the Genesis patriarchal narratives.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The distinction between "children of the flesh" (<em>tekna tēs sarkos</em>) and "children of the promise" (<em>tekna tēs epangelias</em>) connects directly to the argument of ch4 (Abraham\'s faith, not circumcision, constitutes the promise-heir) and to Galatians 4:21-31 (the Hagar-Sarah allegory). In all three contexts Paul uses the same underlying principle: the divine promise defines the people, not ethnic/biological descent. This was not entirely without OT precedent: Deuteronomy repeatedly warns that ethnic Israel can be cut off from the covenant people through faithlessness (Deut 29:18-21).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The promise of Isaac\'s birth in Gen 18:10, 14 was made to Abraham and Sarah when they were both beyond natural child-bearing age (Gen 18:11-12; Heb 11:11-12). The birth of Isaac was therefore understood in Jewish tradition as a miraculous divine act, demonstrating that the promise-line depends on divine creativity rather than human biology. Jewish midrashim on the birth of Isaac emphasize the supernatural character of the event (Gen. Rabbah 53:3 on the re-opening of Sarah\'s womb).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The Rebecca-Jacob-Esau narrative (Gen 25:19-26) was interpreted in Jewish tradition as establishing the principle of divine election. The book of Jubilees 35-36 presents Jacob as the legitimate heir of Abraham\'s blessing and Esau as justly excluded because of his character (though Paul emphasizes that the election was made before either was born or had done good or evil). Rabbinic traditions debated whether Esau\'s rejection was foreknown from his pre-natal character or purely arbitrary — the same debate Paul is engaging.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The pre-birth timing of the Jacob-Esau election was fundamental to Paul\'s argument against works-righteousness as the basis of divine election. The rabbis who believed that God foreknew Esau\'s wickedness before birth still maintained a connection between election and future conduct; Paul\'s emphasis on the pure independence of God\'s purpose (<em>kata prothesin kat\' eklogēn</em>) is more radical. The Dead Sea Scrolls (1QS 3:13-4:26) present a similar pre-determinism: the two spirits (truth and falsehood) are assigned before birth, though with different theological framing.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The oracle of Gen 25:23 that "the older will serve the younger" was understood in Jewish tradition to refer to the nations descending from the twins (Israel from Jacob, Edom from Esau) rather than merely to the twins themselves. The history of Israel-Edom relations — including Edom\'s hostility at the fall of Jerusalem (Ps 137:7; Obad 1:10-14) and Idumean political subjugation to Hasmonean Israel in the 2nd century BCE — gave the oracle historical-political dimensions that Paul\'s readers would have known.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Malachi 1:2-3 was written approximately 450-400 BCE, addressing the post-exilic Jewish community\'s complaint that God had not loved them. God\'s response cites the Jacob-Esau election as evidence of his preferential love for Israel: "Was not Jacob Esau\'s brother? Yet I have loved Jacob, but Esau I have hated." In Malachi, the "hatred" of Esau refers concretely to God\'s treatment of Edom\'s land (v3b: "I have turned his hill country into a wasteland"). The Semitic idiom of loving/hating as preferential choice (cf. Luke 14:26 / Matt 10:37) is operative in the original context as well as in Paul\'s citation.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The charge of divine unrighteousness (<em>adikia</em>) was a serious accusation in Jewish legal theology. God was defined as the righteous judge who does not show partiality and does not take bribes (Deut 10:17; Job 34:12: "Far be it from God to do evil, from the Almighty to do wrong"). The question "Is there unrighteousness with God?" is therefore not a philosophical abstraction but a challenge to the fundamental character of God as Israel knew him. Paul\'s answer from Exodus and the narrative of Pharaoh is that divine sovereignty and divine justice are not in tension — they are both expressions of the same holy character.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The Exodus 33:19 text comes from the theophany scene on Sinai in which Moses asks to see God\'s glory, and God responds by proclaiming his name and passing before Moses. The divine self-declaration ("I will have mercy on whom I have mercy") is embedded in the most intimate divine-human encounter in the OT — the Sinai covenant renewal after the golden calf apostasy. The context is significant: Israel had just sinned grievously, and God is asserting his freedom to show mercy despite the sin. Paul uses the text to ground divine mercy in the divine character, not in human worthiness.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The two Greek verbs for "will" and "run" in v16 evoke the philosophical debate about human freedom and divine providence. The Stoics held that virtue was a matter of will and effort; Philo similarly emphasized human striving toward God. Paul\'s categorical denial that salvation "depends on the one who wills or runs" does not eliminate human response (Paul calls for faith throughout Romans) but denies that human will or effort is the ground or cause of salvation. The exclusive grounding in divine mercy is characteristic of Paul\'s grace-soteriology.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Pharaoh\'s hardening in the Exodus narrative was interpreted in multiple ways in Jewish tradition. Some saw it as God\'s anticipation of Pharaoh\'s already-existing hardness (Philo, Moses 1.147); others saw it as purely divine action (Josephus presents a softer version in Ant. 2.293-314). The specific citation of Exod 9:16 ("I raised you up for this very purpose") reflects the Jewish tradition of reading Pharaoh\'s entire existence as part of God\'s providential plan to display his power and make his name known throughout the earth. Paul uses this to establish divine sovereignty over history at both the individual and cosmic levels.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The divine hardening of Pharaoh (Exod 4:21; 7:3; 9:12; 10:1, 20, 27; 11:10; 14:4, 8, 17) alternates in Exodus with Pharaoh\'s own self-hardening (Exod 8:15, 32; 9:34) in a way that resists simple either-or resolution. Jewish and Christian interpreters have long debated whether the divine hardening is judicial (God confirming and intensifying a hardness Pharaoh chose) or causal (God directly producing Pharaoh\'s resistance). Paul\'s point is not primarily about the mechanism of hardening but about the absolute freedom of divine sovereignty — God hardens "whomever he wills."</p>',
    "19": '<p>The objector\'s question "who has resisted his will?" echoes debates in Hellenistic philosophy about fate and freedom. The Stoics held that divine providence (fate) was inescapable; the Epicureans opposed the concept of fate as threatening human autonomy. Jewish apocalyptic literature similarly wrestled with the tension between divine predetermination and human accountability. Paul\'s answer in v20 does not resolve the philosophical question but reframes it: the creature asking the question is already committed a category error by imagining itself as the questioner rather than as the questioned.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The potter-clay image appears in multiple OT contexts: Isaiah 29:16 ("You turn things upside down! Shall the potter be regarded as the clay?"), Isaiah 45:9 ("Woe to him who quarrels with his Maker, to him who is but a potsherd among the potsherds on the ground"), and Jeremiah 18:1-12 (Jeremiah at the potter\'s house). The Wisdom of Solomon 15:7-8 uses the same image for human mortality: the potter shapes mortal creatures from the same clay. Paul uses the image to establish the Creator\'s absolute prerogative over creation, not to deny creaturely significance or responsibility.</p>',
    "21": '<p>In the ancient world, pottery was one of the most basic and ubiquitous crafts. A Roman or Jewish audience would have immediately understood the potter-clay image from everyday experience. The potter\'s absolute authority over the same lump of clay to make both honorable (<em>eis timēn</em>) and dishonorable (<em>eis atimian</em>) vessels was self-evident. "Honorable" vessels were those used in sacred contexts (for religious use, for honored guests); "dishonorable" vessels were those used for common or waste purposes. The distinction maps onto the vessels of mercy/wrath that follow in vv22-23.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The "vessels of wrath prepared for destruction" have been debated in relation to the "vessels of mercy prepared for glory." The passive <em>katērtismena</em> (prepared) in v22 may be deliberate: Paul does not say God actively prepared the wrath-vessels (as he does with the mercy-vessels in v23 using the active <em>proētoimasen</em>). Some interpreters read this as indicating that the vessels of wrath prepared themselves through persistent rebellion; others maintain a full double predestination. The ambiguity is likely intentional, keeping the theodicy question open while asserting divine sovereignty in both cases.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The Qumran texts use similar vessel imagery for the elect and the reprobate: the "sons of light" and "sons of darkness" are vessels prepared by God\'s eternal decree for their respective destinies (1QS 3:13-4:26; 1QM 13:9-10). Paul stands in an apocalyptic-election tradition but with the crucial difference that the "vessels of mercy" are now identified not with Israel-according-to-the-flesh but with the mixed community of Jews and Gentiles who have believed in the Messiah. The election has been expanded and redefined around Christ.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The identification of "us" (the vessels of mercy) as including both Jews and Gentiles is the theological conclusion Paul has been building toward since ch1. The Gentile mission was not an afterthought to the gospel but was embedded in the prophetic promises of the OT — as the Hosea and Isaiah citations that follow demonstrate. The idea that Gentiles would share in Israel\'s blessings was present in Isaiah\'s vision of the nations flowing to Zion (Isa 2:2-4; 60:1-3), though the mechanism (faith in Israel\'s Messiah) was not fully anticipated.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The book of Hosea addressed the northern kingdom of Israel in the 8th century BCE, when Israel\'s faithlessness had so compromised the covenant that God declared them "not my people" and "not my loved one" (<em>Lo-Ammi</em> and <em>Lo-Ruhamah</em>, Hos 1:6-9). The restoration promise of Hos 2:23 and 1:10 was that the Not-My-People would again become My-People. Paul\'s application of this originally-Israel text to Gentiles is a typological reading: the pattern of Not-My-People becoming My-People is fulfilled in the Gentile inclusion, an even more radical version of what Hosea had announced for faithless Israel.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The phrase "sons of the living God" (<em>huioi theou zōntos</em>) elevates the restoration beyond mere covenant membership to the status of divine sonship. In Hosea\'s context, the restoration of Israel as God\'s people was itself remarkable; the elevation to "sons of God" is an eschatological heightening. Paul reads in Hosea a pattern that the gospel has now actualized for all peoples: the Not-My-People who become sons of God is the story of the Gentile church.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Isaiah\'s remnant theology (Isa 10:22-23) was developed in response to the Assyrian crisis (722 BCE, fall of Samaria) and the Babylonian threat to Judah. The remnant (<em>she\'ar</em> in Hebrew, <em>kataleimma/hypoleimma</em> in LXX) is the purified core that survives divine judgment — not because of their superior righteousness but because of divine grace. This remnant-theology became fundamental for Second Temple Judaism\'s self-understanding after the Babylonian exile: the returning exiles were the remnant. Paul applies it again: within ethnic Israel, the believing remnant of Paul\'s day is the current instantiation of the prophetic remnant.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Isaiah 10:23 speaks of a comprehensive and swift divine judgment on the nations, including the use of Assyria as the instrument. The "word completing and cutting short" images God\'s decisive, efficient judgment-speech. Paul cites it in a context where the "cutting short" applies to Israel\'s partial unbelief: God has accomplished the judgment (the hardening of much of Israel) quickly and without remainder. The citation establishes that the present situation of Jewish unbelief is not an unexpected disruption of God\'s plan but its fulfillment according to Isaiah\'s prophecy.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Isaiah 1:9 comes from the opening oracle of Isaiah — addressed to Jerusalem as a city as corrupt as Sodom and Gomorrah. The "seed" (<em>sperma</em>) that the Lord left is the remnant within Judah that distinguished it from total destruction like Sodom and Gomorrah. Paul uses this text to establish that Israel\'s continuation as a people — even in partial unbelief — represents divine mercy preserving a remnant. Without that divine intervention, Israel would have been completely destroyed by its own faithlessness. The God who preserved a remnant in Isaiah is the same God who preserves a remnant in Paul\'s day.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The paradox of Gentiles who were not pursuing righteousness obtaining it while Israel that was pursuing it did not obtain it reflects the scandal of the gospel in its first-century context. In Jewish theology, the Gentiles (the <em>goyim</em>) were by definition outside the covenant and therefore outside the righteousness that Torah-keeping conferred. That they should receive the covenant blessing (righteousness) without Torah-observance was theologically subversive. Paul presents this not as a human accident but as an eschatological fulfillment of the OT pattern (Hos 2:23; Isa 65:1) in which the unexpected recipients receive God\'s grace.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The image of "pursuing a law of righteousness" (<em>diōkōn nomon dikaiosynēs</em>) evokes the Greek athletic idiom of running a race — Israel as the zealous competitor in the race toward righteousness. The irony that the runner did not "arrive at" (<em>eph\' on nomon ouk ephthasen</em>) the law of righteousness echoes the athletic/competitive culture of the Greco-Roman world where Paul\'s letters circulated. The Corinthian correspondence (1 Cor 9:24-27) shows Paul using similar athletic imagery. Failure to arrive at the goal despite earnest effort represents the deepest kind of religious disappointment.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The stone of stumbling imagery draws on a rich vein of OT texts. Isaiah 8:14 (a stone of stumbling and rock of offense) was written in the context of the Syro-Ephraimite crisis: the "stone" was God himself, who would be either a sanctuary or a trap for Israel depending on their response to his word. Isaiah 28:16 promises a "cornerstone in Zion, a tested stone, a precious cornerstone for a sure foundation." Early Christianity read these two Isaianic texts together as referring to Christ (see 1 Pet 2:6-8; cf. Luke 20:17-18): the same stone that is the foundation for believers is the stumbling block for unbelief.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The composite citation of Isa 28:16 and 8:14 is found in the same combination in 1 Peter 2:6-8, suggesting that this pairing was a fixed testimonia (collection of OT proof-texts) in early Christian tradition, likely originating in Jewish-Christian exegetical circles. The Dead Sea Scrolls provide evidence that OT texts were similarly gathered around themes in pesher commentaries; the early church followed the same midrashic practice of reading OT texts together when they shared common terminology. "The one who believes in him will not be put to shame" provides the promise-counterpart to the stumbling-block warning: the same stone that trips the unbeliever anchors the believer.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>Paul\'s combination of <em>eudokia tēs kardias</em> (heartfelt desire) and <em>deēsis</em> (petition/prayer) reflects the Jewish prayer tradition in which the worshiper expresses both what they want (<em>ratzon</em> = goodwill, desire) and the formal petition before God. The Amidah prayers explicitly combine these elements. Paul positions himself as an intercessor for Israel in the tradition of Moses and Jeremiah — both of whom prayed earnestly for their people despite divine judgment on the people\'s faithlessness. The prayer-frame around the theological argument maintains the pastoral character of the discourse.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Jewish "zeal for God" (<em>zēlōtēs</em>) had a specific historical profile in Paul\'s world. The Maccabean martyrs (2 Macc 4-7) were the paradigm of zeal; Phinehas (Num 25:7-8) was the archetypal zealot who killed to protect the covenant. The Sicarii and Zealot movement of Paul\'s time carried this tradition in its political-military form. Paul had been this kind of zealot (Gal 1:14; Phil 3:6: "as to zeal, persecuting the church"). His diagnosis that zeal without knowledge (<em>epignōsis</em>) leads to wrong action is therefore autobiographical as well as analytical.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The phrase "their own righteousness" (<em>tēn idian dikaiosynēn</em>) became central in later debates between Pelagians and Augustine about self-achieved vs. grace-given righteousness. In Paul\'s first-century context the primary referent is more specific: the righteousness of Torah-observance that marked the Jewish community as the covenant people. The issue is not individualistic self-improvement but the community marker of Torah-faithfulness as the boundary between Israel and the nations. Paul\'s point is that this boundary-marker, while genuinely valued by God, was never intended to be the mechanism of justification before God.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The debate over <em>telos</em> in v4 has engaged interpreters since at least the early church fathers. Origen and many Eastern Fathers read it as "goal/fulfillment" (Christ brings the law to its intended purpose); Augustine and the Western tradition often read it as "end/termination" (Christ brings the law\'s period of dominance to a close). Luther\'s emphasis on "end" was crucial for Reformation theology; the New Perspective on Paul (Sanders, Dunn, Wright) returns to "goal" or "end of the law as an ethnic boundary-marker." Both readings are supported by Paul\'s broader argument: the law\'s purpose (pointing to righteousness) and the law\'s period as the righteousness-mechanism both reach their conclusion in Christ.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The citation of Lev 18:5 ("the person who does these things will live by them") was foundational in Jewish theology as the promise of covenant life for obedience. Ezekiel 20:11 and Nehemiah 9:29 repeat the same principle. Paul had already cited it in Galatians 3:12 as defining the law\'s logic: the law-sphere operates by doing and living. The contrast with Hab 2:4 ("the righteous shall live by faith") that Paul deploys in Galatians and Romans (1:17) establishes that the two "living" principles — by doing vs. by faith — are distinct and ultimately incompatible as mechanisms of standing before God.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Deuteronomy 30:11-14 in its original context argued that the commandment was not impossibly distant (neither in heaven nor across the sea) but near, accessible, in the mouth and heart of the Israelite. Moses was arguing for the Torah\'s practicability. Paul reads the passage through a Christological hermeneutic: the "word" that is near is the gospel word about Christ, and the heaven/sea questions become questions about the necessity of Incarnation (ascending to bring Christ down) and Resurrection (descending to bring Christ up from the dead). This hermeneutical move is similar to the pesher method at Qumran, where OT texts are read as referring to the community\'s present situation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The <em>abyssos</em> (abyss, the underworld, the deep) appears in LXX Ps 106:26 and other OT texts as the watery depths of the sea or the realm of the dead. Paul substitutes "abyss" for Deuteronomy\'s "sea" to make the connection to the underworld explicit: the concern is not oceanography but the resurrection. Jewish cosmology placed Sheol/Hades in the depths below; Christ\'s descent to the dead (implied in the resurrection narrative) is what Paul\'s interpretation of Deut 30:13 addresses. The substitution shows Paul reading Deuteronomy through the lens of Christ\'s death and resurrection.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The accessibility of the "word of faith" (<em>rhēma tēs pisteōs</em>) that Paul and his colleagues preach fulfills what Deuteronomy promised about the Torah: God\'s word is near, not distant. Paul claims that the gospel word is the fulfillment of Deuteronomy\'s promise — the Torah\'s own promise of nearness is now actualized in the gospel proclamation. This is not a dismissal of the Torah but its fulfillment: what the Torah promised (accessible life-giving word in your mouth and heart) has arrived in the form of the gospel about Christ.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The early Christian confession <em>Kyrios Iēsous</em> (Jesus is Lord) was simultaneously a theological declaration and a political one in the context of the Roman empire. The imperial cult, especially prominent in the eastern provinces of Rome, used <em>kyrios</em> (Lord) as a title for the emperor (e.g., Domitian: <em>dominus et deus</em> = lord and god; Nero in papyri: <em>ho kyrios tou kosmou</em> = the Lord of the world). Confessing Jesus as Lord in this political environment was a declaration that Caesar was not the ultimate Lord — a potentially seditious claim. The Roman Christians to whom Paul writes would have been keenly aware of these political dimensions.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The heart-mouth structure of v10 reflects ancient Mediterranean anthropology in which the heart was the seat of will and understanding, and the mouth the organ of public declaration and commitment. In Jewish law and culture, the oral declaration (especially in the context of vows, oaths, and legal proceedings) was the binding verbal act: what was in the heart became legally and socially real when spoken aloud. Paul\'s formulation reflects this understanding: inner faith becomes saving when externalized in confession — not because the words themselves save but because confession is the necessary expression of genuine inner reality.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The repeated emphasis on "everyone" (<em>pas</em>) and "no distinction" (<em>ou diastolē</em>) in vv11-13 is the practical consequence of the theological argument. In first-century Judaism, access to the covenant blessings was typically structured around Jewish identity (circumcision, Torah-observance, temple participation). The Gentile "God-fearers" who attended synagogue had partial access but were not full members. Paul\'s claim that "everyone who believes" without distinction has the same access to the righteousness-promise represents a restructuring of the covenant community around Christ rather than Torah-observance.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The social distance between Jews and Greeks (Romans) in the first century was real and legally structured. Roman law made distinctions between citizens and non-citizens, freeborn and freedmen, Jews and Gentiles. Jewish communities maintained their own communal identity through dietary laws, Sabbath observance, and social separation from Gentile practices. Paul\'s "no distinction" cuts across these legal and social barriers with a theological claim: the same Lord is Lord of all, and "all" who call upon him receive the same richness (<em>ploutōn</em> = riches, abundance) of divine response.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Joel 2:32 (3:5 MT) was cited by Peter at Pentecost (Acts 2:21) as being fulfilled in the Spirit\'s outpouring on "all flesh" — Jew and Gentile alike. The early Christian community thus connected the universal scope of "everyone who calls on the name of the Lord" with the universal scope of Pentecost\'s Spirit-gift. Paul\'s citation of the same text in Romans affirms the same connection: the eschatological day of the Lord described by Joel has arrived in the Christ-event, and the "calling upon the name" is now accessible to all peoples.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The evangelistic logic-chain of vv14-15 reflects Paul\'s own missionary theology and practice. As an apostle commissioned to the Gentiles (Gal 2:7-8), Paul understood his preaching mission as the necessary mechanism through which the promises of Joel and Isaiah would be fulfilled. The chain (sending → preaching → hearing → believing → calling → saving) is Paul\'s theological justification for the apostolic mission, rooted in OT promise. Without missionaries who are sent, the universal promise cannot be universally fulfilled.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Isaiah 52:7 belongs to the Second Isaiah section that envisions the return from Babylonian exile and the restoration of Jerusalem. The herald who announces "good news" of peace and salvation to Zion was originally the messenger running ahead of the returning exiles. In Jewish liturgy the verse was associated with the messianic era and the announcement of God\'s reign. Paul identifies the Christian missionaries as the fulfillment of this Isaiah vision: the good news they proclaim is the messianic good news Isaiah anticipated, and their feet are beautiful because of what they carry.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Isaiah 53:1 opens the fourth Servant Song with a lament that the Servant\'s report has not been believed. In its original context, the question expresses the prophet\'s grief that Israel did not recognize the suffering Servant\'s role. The NT consistently reads Isa 53 as referring to Christ (see Matt 8:17; Luke 22:37; John 12:38; Acts 8:32-33; 1 Pet 2:22-25). Paul uses v1 to establish OT precedent for Israel\'s unbelief in the gospel: Isaiah already mourned that the Servant\'s message was rejected, and this fulfills rather than contradicts the prophetic pattern.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The summary statement "faith comes from hearing" (<em>hē pistis ex akoēs</em>) reflects Paul\'s understanding of how the gospel operates. In Jewish tradition, hearing the Torah read aloud was the primary mode of religious formation (the Shema: "Hear, O Israel" — Deut 6:4). Paul adopts this auditory model of faith-formation but replaces Torah-hearing with gospel-hearing: the word (<em>rhēma</em>) of Christ is the new Torah, and hearing it is the mechanism through which faith is generated. This is not intellectual assent but the receptive hearing that the OT associates with covenant response (Isa 55:3; Ezek 3:10).</p>',
    "18": '<p>Psalm 19 moves from the "wordless speech" of creation (vv1-6) to the life-giving word of Torah (vv7-11). Paul cites the cosmological section (Ps 19:4: "their voice has gone out into all the earth") to answer "have they not heard?" — not the cosmic hearing of nature but the missionary hearing of the gospel. The use of a creation-text for the gospel\'s reach implies that the gospel proclamation has a creation-wide scope analogous to the creation\'s wordless witness. Some interpreters see an implicit connection to Paul\'s natural revelation argument in 1:18-23.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Deuteronomy 32 (the Song of Moses) was one of the most important texts in Second Temple Judaism for understanding Israel\'s history: it describes Israel\'s future apostasy and God\'s subsequent judgment, including the use of a "non-nation" to provoke Israel to jealousy. The Song was recited as part of Jewish liturgy and was among the Dead Sea Scroll texts (multiple copies of Deut 32 found at Qumran). Paul reads the "non-nation" (<em>ouk ethnos</em>) as the Gentile church and the jealousy-provocation as the mechanism through which Israel will ultimately be saved (see 11:11-14).</p>',
    "20": '<p>Isaiah 65:1-2 comes from the final section of Isaiah addressing the post-exilic community\'s expectation of divine intervention. Isaiah 65:1 describes God found by those who did not seek him; Isaiah 65:2 describes God stretching out his hands to rebellious Israel. Paul uses the two halves to distinguish the Gentile mission (v1 = Gentiles finding God unexpectedly) from Israel\'s ongoing situation (v2 = God reaching toward disobedient Israel). The sequential structure mirrors Paul\'s "to the Jew first and also to the Greek" principle of Romans 1:16: God has reached in both directions, with different outcomes so far.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The posture of God stretching out his hands (<em>exepetasa tas cheiras mou</em>) toward disobedient Israel is one of the most anthropomorphic images in Isaiah. The outstretched hands evoke simultaneously the posture of welcome, of pleading, of the teacher inviting response, and (in retrospect for Christian readers) of the crucifixion. Some early Christian interpreters (Justin Martyr, Irenaeus) read the outstretched hands of Isa 65:2 as a direct prophecy of the cross. Whether or not Paul intends this resonance, the image of God continuously reaching toward a disobedient people prepares for ch11\'s argument that God has not rejected Israel but is still reaching.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'romans')
    merge_comm(existing, ROMANS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'romans', existing)
    print('Romans 8–10 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
